Research web performance metrics, specifically Core Web Vitals and their thresholds, and how they relate to business outcomes. Cover the current Core Web Vitals set as of 2024-2025: Largest Contentful Paint (LCP), Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS), Interaction to Next Paint (INP), and Time to First Byte (TTFB). For each metric, provide: the Google-defined Good/Needs Improvement/Poor thresholds, the measurement methodology (what does "75th percentile of field data" mean in this context?), and the technical factors that most commonly cause poor scores.

Research the relationship between web performance metrics and business outcomes: what published studies connect LCP, INP, and CLS improvements to conversion rate, bounce rate, and revenue? Cover Google's own research on performance and user behavior, as well as third-party studies from Akamai, Cloudflare, and e-commerce operators. What is the documented revenue impact of a 100ms improvement in page load time?

Cover the Lighthouse scoring model: how does Lighthouse compute its composite performance score from individual metrics? What are the current metric weightings, and how have they changed across Lighthouse versions 6-12? How does the Lighthouse lab score differ from real-user (field) CrUX data, and why do they frequently diverge?

Research the HTTP Archive and Chrome User Experience Report (CrUX) as data sources: what percentile of pages in the HTTP Archive pass Core Web Vitals thresholds? What are the median LCP, CLS, and INP values across the top 1 million websites?

Cover emerging web performance metrics: Total Blocking Time (TBT), Speed Index, Time to Interactive (TTI), First Contentful Paint (FCP) — which of these are still used and which have been deprecated or de-emphasized in favor of newer metrics?
